solution.p:
Now all the ways to distribute the 18 units to the four y_i variables can be found using stars and bars, specifically 18 stars and 3 bars, so {21 \choose 18} ways. But this includes the ways that one or more y_i variables can be assigned more than 3 units. So subtract using PIE to get

\displaystyle{                {21 \choose 3} -\left( {4\choose 1} {14 \choose 3}-{4\choose 2} {7 \choose 3} + \dots \right)
              }

